"options":["Class I","Class II","Class III","Class IV","Class V"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organization (WHO) functional classification for pulmonary hypertension is adapted from the New York Heart Association (NYHA) classification. The classes are defined as:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass I\u003C/strong\u003E: Patients with pulmonary hypertension without limitation of physical activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass II\u003C/strong\u003E: Patients with slight limitation of physical activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass III\u003C/strong\u003E: Patients with marked limitation of physical activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass IV\u003C/strong\u003E: Patients with symptoms at rest and inability to carry out any physical activity without discomfort\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no \u003Cstrong\u003EClass V\u003C/strong\u003E in the WHO functional classification system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has symptoms at rest and cannot perform any physical activity without symptoms, which clearly places them in Class IV.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["WHO/NYHA functional class IV in pulmonary hypertension is characterized by symptoms at rest and inability to carry out any physical activity without discomfort","Right heart failure is a common complication of advanced pulmonary arterial hypertension"],"references":["Taichman DB, McGoon MD, Harhay MO, Archer-Chicko C, Sager JS, Murugappan M, Chakinali MM, Palevsky HI, Gallop R. Wide variation in clinicians\u0027 assessment of New York Heart Association/World Health Organization functional class in patients with pulmonary arterial hypertension. Mayo Clin Proc. 2009 Jul;84(7):586-92. doi: 10.1016/S0025-6196(11)60747-7. PMID: 19567712; PMCID: PMC2704130.","Tuder RM. Pathology of pulmonary arterial h